We’ve seen this in history time and time again such as when European invaders came into contact with indiginous people using beads for currency. Europeans mass manufactured beads, taking their goods, devaluing their currency and leaving them impoverished. (6)
When hard money comes in contact with a softer money (money that’s easy to produce or counterfeit), the latter tends to get devalued. (5)
As a result, Bitcoin is arguably the “hardest” form of money that has ever existed. A hard currency is characterized by its scarcity and difficulty in creating more of it. (4)

Scarcity is a hard problem even in the real world. How do you really know the Yeezys you got from StockX are authentic? How do you know the dollar in your wallet isn’t counterfeit?  Bitcoin ensures scarcity by using cryptography to track all transactions and ownership. (3)
Bitcoin is the first time that digital scarcity has ever existed.  It’s extremely easy to duplicate things in the digital realm, whether that’s a song, a video, or a meme. (2)

Culture isn’t solely shaped by the will and character of the people in the building but also by the incentives and systems of the industry in which the firm operates. When evaluating career choices, or designing company incentives, game theory can provide a useful framework (fin)

I notice that zero sum industries tend to have more zero sum internal cultures, but that does not necessarily have to be the case if the team deliberately designs internal incentives to be positive sum. (8)

Internal incentives can also be zero sum or positive sum. Eg Teams competing for budget allocation from a fixed pool vs creating budgets from first principles, stack ranking employees vs predetermined metrics for success etc. (7)

Other industries are more fundamentally zero sum. In many sectors of finance, when you win a deal, your competitor loses it. In politics, if you’re elected into office, your opponent loses. As a result people may be less transparent or more likely to undermine others. (6)

The tech industry as a whole is focused on creating exponential value from fixed resources and new products/behaviors and thus has many positive sum characteristics. There are also zero sum scenarios in tech, which are more common as cos get larger (Uber vs Lyft, FB vs Snap) (5)

Working at growing startups can be a unique and refreshing experience in the corporate world because they are so positive sum. If you come up with an idea for a new feature that increases revenues and growth, the entire company is better off. (4)

Zero sum cultures tend to be more competitive and less cooperative as people view the success of others as a threat to their own success. Positive sum cultures tend to be cooperative and innovative as people are focused on growing the pie rather than fighting for slices. (3)

Whether a job or an industry is zero sum or positive sum has a huge impact on culture. In zero sum games, the success of one party comes directly at the expense of another. In contrast, in positive sum games, the success of one party can make all parties better off. (2)

(5) Does Uber need to do more to support drivers? Yes absolutely. But forcing app based companies to treat drivers as employees means fewer jobs. Period.

(4) With Uber/Lyft/Doordash/Instacart they could make money instantly, without having to spend months interviewing and job hunting without pay. When 40% of Americans don’t have $400 saved for an emergency, spending months interviewing means less budget for groceries, rent.

(3) I talked to countess drivers who told me their stories about how they were struggling to find work, recently laid off, or unable to earn enough to provide for their families. Being able to earn money whenever you need it is a game changer.
(2) Scaling UberX across cities was the most fulfilling job of my career. I onboarded drivers, answered their support tickets, gave them my cell phone number to call if they had issues.

@credibleutility Good old pen and paper :)   I asked myself “when did I feel the most fulfilled/excited/motivated in my life?” and tried to distill that out the reasons why.  I removed anything out of my control like the way others perceived me.
Each job, employer, initiative, relationship, success, failure contributes to the body of work that is your career, not the other way around. Your current employer is just one facet. (6-End)

My solution was to take the time to define my personal mission, values and purpose independent of my employer. If my own mission aligned with my employer’s then we are off to the races! If they don’t align, then it’s not too devastating to part ways. (5)

I never want my work to feel like “just a job” as I believe that mentality leads to mediocrity. Could I feel a deep sense of purpose in my work without intertwining my identity with my job? It feels like a paradox. (4)

The negative news spiral and drama around Uber was so personally devastating to me that it impacted my mental health and I realized I had to leave. In the process of leaving, I discovered the uncomfortable truth that I was just another employee. (3)

I joined Uber (a startup at the time) when I was 23. The job consumed me entirely. My  job was my purpose in life and I prioritized it over all else. My team was my family. I took everything negative said about the company personally. (2)
Separating my job/employer from my identity and sense of self-worth did wonders for my mental health, and for my career. (Thread 1/)

7/ Looking back, I wish one of the scrappy hustlers took the reigns as head of marketing and fought hard for a seat at the table. I wish marketing remained more closely aligned with product. I wish we established /simple and clear areas of ownership and rules of engagement.

6/Instead, marketing rolled into either product or ops. The relationships between the orgs was strained. It wasn’t clear if one was supporting the other or vice versa. This led to matrixed orgs across regions/businesses with duplication of effort and lack of clarity on objectives
5/ Uber didn’t hire a CMO for many years. Marketing was a huge driver for growth and a large cost center, but there was never a seat for marketing at the senior leadership table.

4/ The early growth marketers didn’t have fancy resumes, but were scrappy hustlers who found creative ways to get shit done. Many years of marketing experience didn’t necessarily help for a company in hyper-growth creating new consumer behaviors.

3/ Uber’s original marketing team was part of the growth team, a product org. Marketers, engineers, designers, data scientists worked side by side. This was extremely effective , but was hard to scale. Eventually, marketing needed to be spun out.

2/ Uber could not have grown exponentially without marketing. Period. The original Uber growth marketing team was the best of the best and are now founders, VPs (and VCs :P) at the next generation of startups.

Reading your replies, I notice many people equating valuation/stage with risk.   While often correlated, they are not the same. Risk is a function of product, traction, team, biz model etc. Valuation is a negotiation between a small group at a single point in time.

The real “unicorns” for startup employees are the opportunities at companies that have really started to work, but have not yet raised a large growth round. Those are de-risked career-making opportunities. Uber right after UberX launched for example...

@adam_zethraeus Capital obviously is very important for growth, as we both know from Uber, but it’s hard to isolate the impact due to many confounding variables. Leveraging capital to gain enough market leadership to unlock scale economies and network effects is a great strategy IMO

@JonahLupton All of those are very valid factors, but I would look at them from first principles rather than using valuation as a proxy. A startup could be cash flow positive and not need to raise money, so they wouldnt have a fancy valuation, but they would still be a great business.

@sgondala2 Ask about growth, retention, how they find their customers, the long term vision and team they have. Most startups are pretty open. Then do your own homework on the market, the problem they’re solving, competitors, incumbents, long term competitive advantage.

@sgondala2 I disagree about the likelihood to exit. If you are earlier, you have many more exit options that would still result in a good return for shareholders. When you have a very high valuation, your options are more limited to IPO or acquisition by a giant.

@sgondala2 Startups tend to be pretty open about their growth goals, the long term vision, the market they are tackling. While you might not get EBITDA margins, you can get a good sense of market, growth and team.
@magdalenakala When I was first joining Uber, I was a total n00b and has no idea what the difference was between the different VCs 😂 Ironic now, but I can empathize.

If you’re an investor this sounds super obvious but I’ve actually lost candidates at portfolio cos because they wanted to join “unicorns.” Even if the unicorns were priced well ahead of the business. Joining A company at $300M vs $3B has an order of magnitude of upside difference

If you’re looking to join a startup, you maximize upside when you join at a LOWER valuation, esp. when the business is hitting an inflection point.   Too many candidates gravitate to valuation as the most important metric. The higher the valuation, the lower your upside potential
